<pretext>
    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="sec-I-5-sols">
        <title><m>\S I.5</m>: Predicate Logic and Quantifiers</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace=".25in">
                    <title>Motivation: Quantifiers </title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We have symbols to write down useful logical statements that have truth values:
                            <me>
                                \neg, \wedge, \vee, \to, \longleftrightarrow
                            </me>
                            We're missing symbols that help us quantify elements in a statement. For example, we need
                            logical symbols to help us say true/false statements like:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            "Every integer is even."
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            "There is an integer that is even."
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace=".5in">
                    <title>Definition: Quantifiers and Predicates</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            The symbol "<m>\forall</m>" reads "for all". The symbol "<m>\exists</m>" reads "there exists".
                            These symbols are called <term>quantifiers</term>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            A <term>predicate</term> for a universal set <m>U</m> is a sentence including a variable <m>x</m>
                            such that if we replace <m>x</m> with an element of <m>U</m>, we get a proposition (a statement
                            that is unambiguously true or false). 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            An example is that if <m>p(x)</m> is the predicate <m>x-2=0</m>, then <m>p(x)</m> is true
                            for <m>x=2</m> but false otherwise.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Predicates can also have multiple variables. For example, <m>q(x,y)</m> could be the predicate
                            <m>x+1 = y</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace=".5in">
                    <title>Using Quantifiers with Predicates</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Many mathematical statements are formed by attaching quantifiers to predicates.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            As an example, consider the sets
                            <me>
                                E=\{ x \in \N | x \text{ is even}\} \,\, D= \{ x \in \N | x \text{ is odd}\}
                            </me>
                            Write down the meaning of the following logical statements:
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\forall x \in E : (x+1) \in D</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\forall x,y \in D : x+y \in E</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\forall x \in E \exists y \in \Z : x= -y </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Every even number plus one is an odd number.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        The sum of any two odd numbers is an even number.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        For every positive even number <m>x</m> there is an integer
                                        whose negation is <m>x</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

            </page>


            <page>
                <exercise workspace=".5in">
                    <title>Exercise: Order Matters!</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Pick the single true statement below:
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>
                                            \forall x \in \Z \exists y \in \Z : y = x+1
                                        </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>
                                           \exists y \in \Z \forall x \in \Z  : y = x+1
                                        </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        This says "for every integer, there is another integer that is one more". This is true.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        This says "there is an integer which is one more than every other integer". This is false.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="1in">
                    <title>Negating Quantifiers</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            If a quantified statement is false, its negation is true. How do we negate quantifiers?
                            Let's consider the following examples:
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        "Every integer is even."
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        "There is a real number <m>x</m> such that <m>x^2 \lt 0</m>."
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                        
                        
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Negating this statement is "There is an integer that is not even."
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Negating this statement is "Every real number <m>x</m> satisfies <m>x^2 \geq 0</m>."
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The general negation rules for quantifiers are
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\neg (\forall x : p(x)) = \exists x : \neg p(x)</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\neg (\exists x : p(x)) = \forall x : \neg p(x)</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="1in">
                    <title>Practice: Negating Quantifiers</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p> Negate the following statements:
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\exists x : (\neg p(x) \vee q(x))</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\exists x \forall y : (p(x) \wedge q(y))</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\forall x : p(x) \wedge \neg q(x)</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\forall x \exists y : (\neg p(x)) \vee (\neg q(y))</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>



